# Sovereign Cloud Agent Rules

## Design Philosophy

- **Rapid initialisation**: `make check-env && make add-docker-repo && make upload-* && make ansible-runner && make init-central-argo` = zero-to-platform.
- **Makefile portability**: every OpenShift mutation is a `make` target; rerunnable on any cluster by setting env vars.
- **Make target files**: each make target lives in its own file under `make/*.mk`; the root `Makefile` imports them.
- **OCP Appliance end-goal**: bootstrap pipeline will produce a versioned OCP Appliance image embedding all platform components for sovereign/air-gapped deployment.
- **Developer sandbox**: clone bootstrap → set env → `make` = isolated dev cluster, no shared cluster needed.
- **OC read-only**: `oc`/`kubectl` for investigation only; all mutations via `make` or ArgoCD.

## NON-NEGOTIABLE rules (absolute, never override)

- **NO_SECRETS_IN_GIT**: Zero plaintext or base64-encoded secrets, passwords, tokens, API keys, or credentials of any kind in any file committed to any git repository. All secrets live in Vault, delivered via `ExternalSecret` or `PushSecret`. Violating this rule is an immediate blocking issue.
- **NO_DELETE_SOVEREIGN_NS**: Never delete any namespace prefixed `sovereign-*`. Deletion of these namespaces is permanently prohibited.
- **DEPLOY_AFTER_PHASE**: After completing each phase of work: commit all changes, push to remote, trigger an ArgoCD sync (or `make init-central-argo` for Phase 1 init). No phase is complete without a deployed and healthy state.
- **ARGOCD_ONLY_POST_INIT**: After `make init-central-argo`, all subsequent cluster changes must flow through ArgoCD. `oc apply`, `oc create`, or any direct YAML application is forbidden for configuration changes. Init via Makefile once; ArgoCD owns everything after.

## Non-negotiable constraints

- **Repo boundary**: modify only `bootstrap/` and `architecture/`. Never write to `/` (workspace root).
- **Validate**: run `helm lint` before marking chart work done.
- **Make for oc**: all OpenShift CLI interactions must go through `make` targets.
- **GitOps**: after `make init-central-argo`, all installs must be ArgoCD ApplicationSet driven.
- **Secrets**: all credentials via environment variables, passed through `helm --set`. Never hardcode.
- **Git**: commit and push after each phase. Commit messages: `<type>: <description>`.
- **No git history**: never use git log, git blame, or commit history for context. Only look at the current state of files.
- **Docs**: update `bootstrap/README.md`, Makefile help, and `architecture/docs/` on every meaningful change. **Always update `architecture/docs/` after any architectural or topology change.**
- **Iterate**: deploy → test → fix loop until `Synced + Healthy`. Debug with `oc` read commands.
- **Diagrams**: use Mermaid in `architecture/docs/`. Keep each diagram small and focused (max ~15 nodes). Split complex diagrams into multiple files.
- **Security**: after any chart or Makefile change, review `architecture/hardeningcheck/` and update if findings change.
- **Hardening checks**: at the end of each work cycle, perform hardening checks and update or create entries in `architecture/hardeningcheck/`. Add new component files as components are added.
- **Architecture**: always follow `architecture/docs/` as the source of truth for platform topology.
- **Samples**: keep samples enabled for deployment but provide an enable/disable flag in the corresponding chart values.
- **ExternalSecrets for secrets**: always use `kind: ExternalSecret` for secret consumption and `kind: PushSecret` for secret creation. Never use k8s Secrets with hardcoded values in Helm charts (except the init chart bootstrap phase).
- **Commit and push after each phase**: every phase must end with a git commit and push. No exceptions.
- **Test users**: create test users in Keycloak for testing, then delete users but leave groups intact.
- **ArgoCD resources**: permitted to add ArgoCD resources and reorganize charts/templates/kind:Applications to avoid interdependencies on rollouts.

## Operator placement rules

- **`hybridsovereign.redhat` operators → services cluster**: all operators with API group `hybridsovereign.redhat` (e.g., Entity Operator, plugin_rbac) must be deployed to the **services cluster**. Their CRDs, deployments, and watched namespaces live on services.
- **`helper.hybridsovereign.redhat` operators → central cluster**: all operators with API group `helper.hybridsovereign.redhat` must be deployed to the **central cluster**. Currently none exist; this rule applies to future additions.

## ArgoCD interaction rules

- **Central ArgoCD only**: all ArgoCD interaction must target the central cluster ArgoCD (`openshift-gitops` namespace on central). Never interact with ArgoCD on the services cluster.
- **No ArgoCD on services**: do NOT create, modify, or query ArgoCD Applications/ApplicationSets on the services cluster. The services cluster has NO ArgoCD management.
- **All deployments via central ArgoCD**: every cluster change flows through the central ArgoCD app-of-apps. No direct deployments to either cluster outside of `make` bootstrap targets.
- **AppProject separation**: central cluster resources use `project: central`, services cluster resources use `project: services`. Never mix.

## `oc` / `kubectl` usage rules

- **Investigation and deletion only**: `oc` is permitted for read commands (`get`, `describe`, `logs`, `status`), resource deletion (`oc delete`), and triggering ArgoCD syncs/refreshes (`oc annotate ... argocd.argoproj.io/refresh=hard`) on the **central cluster only**.
- **Never create YAML via oc**: do not use `oc apply -f -`, `oc create`, or pipe YAML into `oc`. All resource creation and mutation must go through Helm charts rendered by ArgoCD.
- **No oc exec**: never use `oc exec` or `kubectl exec` to run commands inside pods. If in-cluster actions are needed, use an Ansible Job deployed via ArgoCD.
- **Deletion via ArgoCD preferred**: the agent may delete resources directly with `oc delete` when necessary, but the preferred method is disabling the component in the app-of-apps (`enabled: false`) and letting ArgoCD prune.

## Change methodology

- **Primary method — app-of-apps**: all cluster changes must flow through the app-of-apps Helm chart (`helm/central`). Add, modify, or disable components there.
- **Secondary method — Ansible via ArgoCD**: if the app-of-apps cannot achieve a change (e.g., imperative API calls, multi-step workflows, waiting for readiness), implement it as an Ansible playbook deployed as a Kubernetes Job via an ArgoCD-managed Helm chart (`helm/charts/*/`).
- **Never ad-hoc**: do not apply ad-hoc YAML, run imperative `oc` mutations, or `oc exec` into pods as a way to make changes.

## Human-readability rules

- **No large files**: any file above 500 lines must be split into multiple files.
- **No large diagrams**: split complex diagrams into multiple small, focused diagrams (max ~15 nodes each).
- **Simple language**: documentation should be understandable by non-technical stakeholders where possible.
- **One concern per file**: each file should have a single clear purpose.

## ArgoCD rules

- **Self-heal**: all ArgoCD Applications must have `selfHeal: true` in their sync policy.
- **Prune**: all ArgoCD Applications must have `prune: true` to remove orphaned resources.
- **Always in sync**: if any ArgoCD Application is not `Synced + Healthy`, investigate and fix immediately.
- **Dynamic plugins**: always enable ArgoCD dynamic plugins when available (e.g., `argocd-vault-plugin`, UI plugins).
- **Single app-of-apps**: there is ONE app-of-apps chart (`helm/central`) containing ALL Applications for BOTH clusters. Services-targeting apps use `destination.server: <services-cluster-url>`.
- **No helm/services**: the `helm/services/` directory must not exist. All services-cluster apps are defined in `helm/central/`.

## NON-NEGOTIABLE: Services cluster ArgoCD restrictions

These rules are absolute and must never be violated under any circumstances:

1. **NEVER create `kind: ApplicationSet` on the services cluster** — not manually, not via Helm, not via any automation.
2. **NEVER create `kind: Application` on the services cluster** — not manually, not via Helm, not via any automation.
3. **All management of the services cluster is done by the central cluster's ArgoCD** using `destination.server` pointing to the services cluster API URL.
4. **Central ArgoCD has two clusters defined**: `https://kubernetes.default.svc` (central) and the services cluster URL. All deployments to services go through this mechanism.
5. **ACM is ONLY on the central cluster** — never install ACM on the services cluster.

## Base-config charts

- **Do NOT sync `base-config-chart` or `base-configs`**: this project does not own them. Never modify, sync, or troubleshoot these ArgoCD applications. Ignore their `OutOfSync` status.

## Ansible playbook development

- **Test locally first**: always test Ansible playbooks locally from this agent (using `ansible-playbook` or `ansible-runner`) before packaging them into a Job or container image.
- **Roles-only playbooks**: playbooks in `bootstrap/ansible/project/` must ONLY call roles. All task logic lives in `bootstrap/ansible/roles/`.
- **Promote to Job after success**: once a playbook is fully functional locally, create a Kubernetes Job (via Helm chart) to run it in-cluster via ArgoCD.

## Credential storage

- **NEVER store credentials locally**: no secrets, tokens, passwords, or keys may be written to the local filesystem. All credentials must be stored in Kubernetes Secrets or HashiCorp Vault. Environment variables are acceptable for session-scoped usage only.

## OCI / Quay rules

- **Robot read-only**: the Quay robot account (`hybrid-sovereign+pull`) must have **read-only** access on all repositories in the `hybrid-sovereign` organization. Use the admin token (`OCI_REGISTRY_TOKEN`) for write operations (repo creation, chart push).
- **Chart push uses admin token**: all `make upload-*` targets authenticate with the admin token for push, not the robot.

## Required Environment Variables

All of the following **must** be set before any `make` target is executed. Never hardcode these values.
`make check-env` verifies them and tests logins.

### Central Cluster
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCP_CENTRAL_SERVER` | Central cluster API URL |
| `OCP_CENTRAL_USERNAME` | Central cluster login username |
| `OCP_CENTRAL_PASSWORD` | Central cluster login password |

### Services Cluster
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCP_SERVICES_SERVER` | Services cluster API URL |
| `OCP_SERVICES_USERNAME` | Services cluster login username |
| `OCP_SERVICES_PASSWORD` | Services cluster login password |

### OCI Registry (admin)
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCI_REGISTRY` | Quay registry hostname or full URL |
| `OCI_REGISTRY_TOKEN` | Admin bearer token (create repos, push charts/images) |

### OCI Registry (robot/read-only)
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCI_ROBOT_USERNAME` | Robot account username — read-only pull |
| `OCI_ROBOT_PASSWORD` | Robot account token |

### Image Registry
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `IMAGE_REGISTRY` | Container image registry (e.g. `registry.redhat.io`) |
| `IMAGE_REGISTRY_USERNAME` | Registry login username |
| `IMAGE_REGISTRY_PASSWORD` | Registry login password/token |

### Git
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `GITHUB_URL` | Repository base URL |
| `GITHUB_TOKEN` | Personal access token (repo scope) |

## Cluster Prerequisites (one-time, manual)

Before running any bootstrap phase, both clusters must have:
1. **OpenShift 4.x** installed
2. **ArgoCD (OpenShift GitOps)** installed and accessible

